## <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#chunkedarray" class="doc-anchor">§</a>ChunkedArray

Every Series contains a [`ChunkedArray<T>`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray"). Unlike [`Series`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.Series.html "struct polars::prelude::Series"), [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray")s are typed. This allows us to apply closures to the data and collect the results to a [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray") of the same type `T`. Below we use an apply to use the cosine function to the values of a [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray").

``` rust
fn apply_cosine_and_cast(ca: &Float32Chunked) -> Float32Chunked {
    ca.apply_values(|v| v.cos())
}
```

### <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#conversion-between-series-and-chunkedarrays" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Conversion between Series and ChunkedArrays

Conversion from a [`Series`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.Series.html "struct polars::prelude::Series") to a [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray") is effortless.

``` rust
fn to_chunked_array(series: &Series) -> PolarsResult<&Int32Chunked>{
    series.i32()
}

fn to_series(ca: Int32Chunked) -> Series {
    ca.into_series()
}
```

## <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#iterators" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Iterators

[`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray")s fully support Rust native [Iterator](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/iter/trait.Iterator.html) and [DoubleEndedIterator](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/iter/trait.DoubleEndedIterator.html) traits, thereby giving access to all the excellent methods available for [Iterators](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/iter/trait.Iterator.html).

``` rust

fn iter_forward(ca: &Float32Chunked) {
    ca.iter()
        .for_each(|opt_v| println!("{:?}", opt_v))
}

fn iter_backward(ca: &Float32Chunked) {
    ca.iter()
        .rev()
        .for_each(|opt_v| println!("{:?}", opt_v))
}
```

## <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#memory-layout" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Memory layout

[`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray")s use [Apache Arrow](https://github.com/apache/arrow) as backend for the memory layout. Arrows memory is immutable which makes it possible to make multiple zero copy (sub)-views from a single array.

To be able to append data, Polars uses chunks to append new memory locations, hence the [`ChunkedArray<T>`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray") data structure. Appends are cheap, because it will not lead to a full reallocation of the whole array (as could be the case with a Rust Vec).

However, multiple chunks in a [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray") will slow down many operations that need random access because we have an extra indirection and indexes need to be mapped to the proper chunk. Arithmetic may also be slowed down by this. When multiplying two [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray")s with different chunk sizes they cannot utilize [SIMD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIMD) for instance.

If you want to have predictable performance (no unexpected re-allocation of memory), it is advised to call the [`ChunkedArray::rechunk`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.rechunk "method polars::prelude::ChunkedArray::rechunk") after multiple append operations.

See also [`ChunkedArray::extend`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.extend "method polars::prelude::ChunkedArray::extend") for appends within a chunk.

## <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#invariants" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Invariants

- A [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray") should always have at least a single [`ArrayRef`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/type.ArrayRef.html "type polars::prelude::ArrayRef").
- The [`PolarsDataType`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/trait.PolarsDataType.html "trait polars::prelude::PolarsDataType") `T` should always map to the correct [`ArrowDataType`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/enum.ArrowDataType.html "enum polars::prelude::ArrowDataType") in the [`ArrayRef`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/type.ArrayRef.html "type polars::prelude::ArrayRef") chunks.
- Nested datatypes such as [`List`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/enum.DataType.html#variant.List "variant polars::prelude::DataType::List") and [`Array`](https://docs.rs/polars-arrow/0.51.0/x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/polars_arrow/array/trait.Array.html "trait polars_arrow::array::Array") store the physical types instead of the logical type given by the datatype.

### impl\<T\> <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html" class="struct" title="struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray">ChunkedArray</a>\<T\>

where T: <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/trait.PolarsNumericType.html" class="trait" title="trait polars::prelude::PolarsNumericType">PolarsNumericType</a>,

#### pub fn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.extend" class="fn">extend</a>(&mut self, other: &<a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html" class="struct" title="struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray">ChunkedArray</a>\<T\>) -\> <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/result/enum.Result.html" class="enum" title="enum core::result::Result">Result</a>\<<a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/std/primitive.unit.html" class="primitive">()</a>, <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/enum.PolarsError.html" class="enum" title="enum polars::prelude::PolarsError">PolarsError</a>\>

Extend the memory backed by this array with the values from `other`.

Different from [`ChunkedArray::append`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.append "method polars::prelude::ChunkedArray::append") which adds chunks to this [`ChunkedArray`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html "struct polars::prelude::ChunkedArray") `extend` appends the data from `other` to the underlying `PrimitiveArray` and thus may cause a reallocation.

However if this does not cause a reallocation, the resulting data structure will not have any extra chunks and thus will yield faster queries.

Prefer `extend` over `append` when you want to do a query after a single append. For instance during online operations where you add `n` rows and rerun a query.

Prefer `append` over `extend` when you want to append many times before doing a query. For instance when you read in multiple files and when to store them in a single `DataFrame`. In the latter case finish the sequence of `append` operations with a [`rechunk`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.rechunk "method polars::prelude::ChunkedArray::rechunk").

<a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#impl-ChunkedArray%3CT%3E-6" class="anchor">§</a>

#### pub fn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.amortized_iter" class="fn">amortized_iter</a>( &self, ) -\> AmortizedListIter\<'\_, impl <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/iter/traits/iterator/trait.Iterator.html" class="trait" title="trait core::iter::traits::iterator::Iterator">Iterator</a>\<Item = <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/option/enum.Option.html" class="enum" title="enum core::option::Option">Option</a>\<<a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/alloc/boxed/struct.Box.html" class="struct" title="struct alloc::boxed::Box">Box</a>\<dyn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars-arrow/0.51.0/x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/polars_arrow/array/trait.Array.html" class="trait" title="trait polars_arrow::array::Array">Array</a>\>\>\>\>

This is an iterator over a [`ArrayChunked`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/type.ArrayChunked.html "type polars::prelude::ArrayChunked") that save allocations. A Series is: 1. [`Arc<ChunkedArray>`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.Arc.html "struct polars::prelude::Arc") ChunkedArray is: 2. Vec\< 3. ArrayRef\>

The [`ArrayRef`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/type.ArrayRef.html "type polars::prelude::ArrayRef") we indicated with 3. will be updated during iteration. The Series will be pinned in memory, saving an allocation for

1.  Arc\<..\>
2.  Vec\<…\>

##### <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#warning" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Warning

Though memory safe in the sense that it will not read unowned memory, UB, or memory leaks this function still needs precautions. The returned should never be cloned or taken longer than a single iteration, as every call on `next` of the iterator will change the contents of that Series.

##### <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#safety-3" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Safety

The lifetime of [AmortSeries](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/series/amortized_iter/struct.AmortSeries.html "struct polars::series::amortized_iter::AmortSeries") is bound to the iterator. Keeping it alive longer than the iterator is UB.

#### pub fn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.amortized_iter_with_name" class="fn">amortized_iter_with_name</a>( &self, name: <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.PlSmallStr.html" class="struct" title="struct polars::prelude::PlSmallStr">PlSmallStr</a>, ) -\> AmortizedListIter\<'\_, impl <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/iter/traits/iterator/trait.Iterator.html" class="trait" title="trait core::iter::traits::iterator::Iterator">Iterator</a>\<Item = <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/option/enum.Option.html" class="enum" title="enum core::option::Option">Option</a>\<<a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/alloc/boxed/struct.Box.html" class="struct" title="struct alloc::boxed::Box">Box</a>\<dyn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars-arrow/0.51.0/x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/polars_arrow/array/trait.Array.html" class="trait" title="trait polars_arrow::array::Array">Array</a>\>\>\>\>

This is an iterator over a [`ArrayChunked`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/type.ArrayChunked.html "type polars::prelude::ArrayChunked") that save allocations. A Series is: 1. [`Arc<ChunkedArray>`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.Arc.html "struct polars::prelude::Arc") ChunkedArray is: 2. Vec\< 3. ArrayRef\>

The ArrayRef we indicated with 3. will be updated during iteration. The Series will be pinned in memory, saving an allocation for

1.  Arc\<..\>
2.  Vec\<…\>

If the returned `AmortSeries` is cloned, the local copy will be replaced and a new container will be set.

#### pub fn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#method.amortized_iter-1" class="fn">amortized_iter</a>( &self, ) -\> AmortizedListIter\<'\_, impl <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/iter/traits/iterator/trait.Iterator.html" class="trait" title="trait core::iter::traits::iterator::Iterator">Iterator</a>\<Item = <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/option/enum.Option.html" class="enum" title="enum core::option::Option">Option</a>\<<a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/alloc/boxed/struct.Box.html" class="struct" title="struct alloc::boxed::Box">Box</a>\<dyn <a href="https://docs.rs/polars-arrow/0.51.0/x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/polars_arrow/array/trait.Array.html" class="trait" title="trait polars_arrow::array::Array">Array</a>\>\>\>\>

This is an iterator over a [`ListChunked`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/type.ListChunked.html "type polars::prelude::ListChunked") that saves allocations. A Series is: 1. [`Arc<ChunkedArray>`](https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.Arc.html "struct polars::prelude::Arc") ChunkedArray is: 2. Vec\< 3. ArrayRef\>

The ArrayRef we indicated with 3. will be updated during iteration. The Series will be pinned in memory, saving an allocation for

1.  Arc\<..\>
2.  Vec\<…\>

If the returned `AmortSeries` is cloned, the local copy will be replaced and a new container will be set.

##### <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#panics-6" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Panics

This function is very opinionated. On the implementation of `ChunkedArray<T>` for numeric types, we assume that all numeric `Series` are of the same type.

In this case we assume that all numeric `Series` are `f64` types. The caller needs to uphold this contract. If not, it will panic.

##### <a href="https://docs.rs/polars/latest/polars/prelude/struct.ChunkedArray.html#panics-5" class="doc-anchor">§</a>Panics

This function is very opinionated. On the implementation of `ChunkedArray<T>` for numeric types, we assume that all numeric `Series` are of the same type.

In this case we assume that all numeric `Series` are `f64` types. The caller needs to uphold this contract. If not, it will panic.
